04070nam a22005175i 9780773570030DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735700307 a10.1515/97807735700302doi  a(DE-B1597)657749  a(OCoLC)244764155  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV6535.C33bG723 2002eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a364.15/23/09719521 aGrant, Shelagh D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArctic Justice :bOn Trial for Murder, Pond Inlet, 1923 /cShelagh D. Grant. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (368 p.) :bIllustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v3300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tPhotographs and Illustrations -- tPreface -- tPrologue -- tNorth Baffin Prior to 1905 -- tSovereignty and Justice, 1874–1920 -- tTraders and Gold-Seekers, 1912-1919 -- tSakirmiaviniq -- tPolice Investigations -- tAwaiting Judgment -- tTrial by Jury -- tTo Prison and Return -- tAftermath -- tArctic Justice Revisited -- tEpilogue -- tAppendices -- tNotes on Research and Inuit Oral History -- tInuit Names for People and Places -- tInuit Glossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the fact that Nuqallaq was following Inuit customary law in carrying out a collectively sanctioned act to defend the community from the dangerously crazed trader Robert Janes, Canadian authorities made the unprecedented decision to put him and two accomplices on trial for murder. Grant shows how this decision was motivated by Canada's international political concerns for establishing sovereignty over the Arctic and how the outcome of the trial - Nuqallaq's sentence to ten years of hard labour in Stony Mountain Penitentiary and subsequent death from tuberculosis - was determined more by fear than evidence. In what amounts to a social history of North Baffin Island in the twentieth century, Grant offers telling portraits of the people involved, including the victim, Robert Janes of Newfoundland; Captain J.E. Bernier of the CGS Arctic, explorer and friend to the Inuit; English trader and entrepreneur Henry Toke Munn; the investigating RCMP officer Staff-Sargeant A. H.; Judge L. A. Rivet, and others. Most importantly we meet the remarkable Nuqallaq, his wife Ataguttiaq, and the Inuit of North Baffin Island. Arctic Justice will appeal to anyone interested in the Arctic and its indigenous peoples, contact history, anthropology, legal history, and RCMP history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773570030?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773570030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773570030/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles